@{
    ViewBag.Title = "Shop";
}

@model List<loudclothes.net.Models.Product>

<div class="container">
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-lg-12">
            <h1 class="page-header">
                Welcome
                <small>in my shop!</small>
            </h1>
            <ol class="breadcrumb">
                <li>
                    @Html.ActionLink("Home", "Index", "Home")
                </li>
                <li class="active">Collection</li>
            </ol>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    @foreach (var pr in Model)
    {
        @Html.ActionLink(pr.Name, "Details", "Portfolio", new { @ProductId = pr.ProductId }, null);
    }




    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-4 portfolio-item">
            <a href="@Url.Action("Item1","Portfolio")">
                <img src="~/images/retro damskie lookbook.jpg" class="img-responsive" />
            </a>
            <h3>
               Retro women's
            </h3>
            <p>Recent proposals Loud Clothes for autumn-winter 2015 women primarily three lines: 1970's LOOKBOOK, Girly Street and Modern Utility. Lines complement each other and form a really interesting fashion proposals for the cooler months.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4 portfolio-item">
            <a href="@Url.Action("Item2","Portfolio")">
                <img src="~/images/sukienka LOOKBOOK.jpg" class="img-responsive" />
            </a>
            <h3>
              Retro women's
            </h3>
            <p>Modern and practical - the name of this line says it all. This trend does not mean boredom, and a completely new styles and very trendy styling without coquetry to shock. The clothes are classic, good every day, to work or school, shopping and weekend meetings with friends.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4 portfolio-item">
            <a href="@Url.Action("Item3","Portfolio")">
                <img src="~/images/szare kolka LOOKBOOK.jpg" class="img-responsive" />
            </a>
            <h3>
                Retro women's
            </h3>
            <p>Sophisticated intellectual, elegant clerk or simply amateur precious fabrics? It's hard to say which type of woman inspired the designers to create this unique looku. It is luxuriously, in a climate of retro and very practical.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-4 portfolio-item">
            <a href="@Url.Action("Item4","Portfolio")">
                <img src="~/images/merkiny1.jpg" class="img-responsive" />
            </a>
            <h3>
               Retro women's
            </h3>
            <p>The base is the styles of the 70 colors is off, only the lively accents of brick red. "70's luxe" is the perfect styling to the office and wherever you need a hint of formality connected with the fashion smartness.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4 portfolio-item">
            <a href="@Url.Action("Item5","Portfolio")">
                <img src="~/images/retro meskie LOOKBOOK 2.jpg" class="img-responsive" />
            </a>
            <h3>
               Retro men's
            </h3>
            <p>Creating a collection for autumn / winter 2015 designer reached for the style of the seventies and broke it touches the style of the late sixties. Collection operates remarkable palette of colors. The duo of white and brown was varied shades of rust, berries, orange or turquoise sea. Retro-Look complement the prints used on jersey tops.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-4 portfolio-item">
            <a href="@Url.Action("Item6","Portfolio")">
                <img src="~/images/retro meskie LOOKBOOK.jpg" class="img-responsive" />
            </a>
            <h3>
              Retro men's
            </h3>
            <p>The collection pays particular attention colors. The basis of effective styling Lookbook layers are. Suitable look effortlessly we build trousers thanks to a high state matching navies, and charming, simple cut. Services 70 years are also evident among the additives.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
    
  
</div>
